---
import PolicyPageLayout from '../../layouts/PolicyPageLayout.astro';

const updatedAt = new Date('2026-07-22');
const sections = [
  { depth: 2, slug: 'what-this-policy-covers', text: 'What this policy covers' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'how-we-choose-coverage', text: 'How we choose coverage' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'evidence-and-sources', text: 'Evidence and sources' },
  {
    depth: 2,
    slug: 'testing-and-demonstration-content',
    text: 'Testing and demonstration content',
  },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'scores-and-verdicts', text: 'Scores and verdicts' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'commercial-independence', text: 'Commercial independence' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'ai-in-the-workflow', text: 'AI in the workflow' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'updates-and-corrections', text: 'Updates and corrections' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'accountability', text: 'Accountability' },
];
---

<PolicyPageLayout
  title="Editorial policy"
  description="How evidique separates evidence, opinion, commercial relationships, corrections, and clearly labeled demonstration content."
  kicker="The rules behind the verdict"
  recordLabel="Editorial standard"
  {updatedAt}
  {sections}
  highlights={[
    'Important claims need a test record, dated source, or visible caveat.',
    'Vendors and commercial partners do not approve our conclusions.',
    'Material errors are corrected with a new visible update date.',
  ]}
>
  <h2 id="what-this-policy-covers">What this policy covers</h2>
  <p>
    This policy applies to reviews, comparisons, alternatives, best-tool lists, guides, and the
    supporting data published by evidique. It explains how we decide what to cover, what counts as
    evidence, and who has the final word.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our job is not to make every tool look good. It is to help solo developers, publishers, and
    small teams understand what a product can do, where it gets awkward, and what it costs today.
  </p>

  <h2 id="how-we-choose-coverage">How we choose coverage</h2>
  <p>
    Editors choose topics based on reader usefulness, meaningful product changes, category demand,
    and whether we can test the central claims. Popularity can put a tool on the list; it cannot
    decide the verdict.
  </p>
  <p>
    Vendors may suggest products or provide access. We do not promise coverage, a publication date,
    or a favorable result in exchange.
  </p>

  <h2 id="evidence-and-sources">Evidence and sources</h2>
  <p>
    Material claims should connect to a repeatable task, captured output, original screenshot,
    product documentation, or another dated primary source. When only secondary reporting is
    available, we identify it and avoid presenting the claim as settled fact.
  </p>
  <p>
    Product features, limits, and pricing can change between checks. Each article displays its
    publication and update dates, and pricing claims should include the date they were verified.
  </p>

  <h2 id="testing-and-demonstration-content">Testing and demonstration content</h2>
  <p>
    We call something hands-on only when an editor used the product for the tasks described. A free
    trial, paid plan, or vendor-provided account may be used, and the access method should be
    disclosed when it could affect the result.
  </p>
  <p>
    Demonstration pages exist to show the publication format while testing is still incomplete. They
    carry a prominent notice. Placeholder scores, sample conclusions, and illustrative results are
    not recommendations.
  </p>

  <h2 id="scores-and-verdicts">Scores and verdicts</h2>
  <p>
    Scores follow the published weighting system in <a href="/how-we-test/">How we test</a>. Editors
    score the evidence collected for the stated audience and use case—not a vendor's feature list or
    a product's reputation.
  </p>
  <p>
    A score is a compact summary, not a substitute for the review. The written verdict, limitations,
    test notes, and pricing context explain what the number cannot.
  </p>

  <h2 id="commercial-independence">Commercial independence</h2>
  <p>
    Affiliate availability, sponsorship, advertising, gifts, and vendor access do not qualify a
    product for coverage or improve its position. Commercial partners cannot preview, approve, or
    suppress an editorial conclusion.
  </p>
  <p>
    Paid placements, if introduced, will sit outside editorial rankings and carry a clear label.
    Affiliate links follow the separate <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/">affiliate disclosure</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="ai-in-the-workflow">AI in the workflow</h2>
  <p>
    AI tools may help transcribe notes, organize an outline, compare drafts, or flag unclear prose.
    They do not receive final editorial authority. A named human editor checks the evidence,
    wording, score, links, and published conclusion.
  </p>
  <p>
    We do not invent tests, quotes, customer experiences, or product behavior to fill a gap. If the
    evidence is missing, the honest answer is to say so or postpone the conclusion.
  </p>

  <h2 id="updates-and-corrections">Updates and corrections</h2>
  <p>
    We review a correction request against primary evidence. When a material error is confirmed, we
    fix it promptly, change the visible update date, and add an editor's note when the correction
    changes the verdict or meaning of the page.
  </p>
  <p>
    Small spelling, formatting, and broken-link fixes may be made without an editor's note. Products
    are re-tested when a change is likely to alter the recommendation, not merely because a release
    note exists.
  </p>

  <h2 id="accountability">Accountability</h2>
  <p>
    Ethan Miller owns this policy and takes responsibility for evidique's published work. Send a
    correction to <a href="mailto:x771364026@gmail.com">x771364026@gmail.com</a> with the page URL, disputed
    claim, source, and date checked.
  </p>
</PolicyPageLayout>
